<div id="review_1783915412" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1783915412" />
    <a title="Sarah Obsesses over Books &amp; Cookies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2070861-sarah-obsesses-over-books-cookies"><img alt="Sarah Obsesses over Books &amp; Cookies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1626961255p2/2070861.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1783915412?book_show_action=true">Oct 23, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah Obsesses over Books &amp; Cookies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah Obsesses over Books &amp; Cookies" href="/user/show/2070861-sarah-obsesses-over-books-cookies">Sarah Obsesses over Books &amp; Cookies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1783915412" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17243294621408562792">McMurtry reminds me a little of John Irving in that he will take a character, usually a secondary one and give this whole rambling back story that can be really boring but works for them. <br/>Terms of Endearment was marketed as a mother-daughter story but I think it was more about Aurora. She is CLASSIC! she comes across as confident and witty and whip-smart (which she is) but really the overconfidence is covering major insecurity. She needs men to make her feel powerful and sexy. She needs to be wa</span>
  <span id="freeText17243294621408562792" style="display:none">McMurtry reminds me a little of John Irving in that he will take a character, usually a secondary one and give this whole rambling back story that can be really boring but works for them. <br />Terms of Endearment was marketed as a mother-daughter story but I think it was more about Aurora. She is CLASSIC! she comes across as confident and witty and whip-smart (which she is) but really the overconfidence is covering major insecurity. She needs men to make her feel powerful and sexy. She needs to be wanted to feel okay about life. Who can't relate to that in some way? She's selfish and obnoxious at times but has one helluva heart. I love her. <br />Aurora is 49 and has a daughter who at the opening of the story tells her she's pregnant. This would usually be good news but to Aurora it's awful, I mean, how is she going to tell all her suiters this and still be a vixen? <br />And Emma (her daughter) is married to Flap who is an asshole and Aurora knows this and the two of them together make for some interesting scenes. <br />So the story goes back and forth between Emma and Aurora and her many adventures with her beaus; namely Alfredo who is an old italian who brings her rooms full of flowers, General Hector Scott who is her neighbor and who is militant in personality and routine and give Aurora a run for her money. And then there's Vernon who Aurora hits with her car when on a date with the General and then leaves with him in his new Cadillac. <br />IT's crazy. <br />But then things get REAL when Emma finds ways to deal with the lack of love and attention in her marriage and then later on it gets worse.<br />I loved this book and can't wait to read the sequel. <br /><br />I watched the movie this morning and it had a stat studded cast but the movie DID NOT follow the book which irritates the hell out of me. Brooks took out a major character and didn't add a ton of the book to the movie and changed the backstory to Vernon. ugh... but it was still good because Shirley Mclane/Jack Nicholson.<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="17243294621408562792" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


