<div id="review_1371092930" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1371092930" />
    <a title="Alex Lee" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11509598-alex-lee"><img alt="Alex Lee" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1343936414p2/11509598.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1371092930?book_show_action=true">Aug 22, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Alex Lee" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Alex Lee" href="/user/show/11509598-alex-lee">Alex Lee</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11509598-alex-lee?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/11509598-alex-lee?shelf=2015">2015</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1371092930" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3129195083501211670">I&apos;m not sure I understood this novel. It would be easy to dismiss the characters because they are too selfish, or too amoral. By today&apos;s standards the violence and verbal abuse seem trivalized as when it&apos;s done, the characters easily forget and bear little to no grudges. I did want to find out what was happening but in the end, it seemed all they wanted to do was mostly drink, screw, and abuse each other because someone else isn&apos;t living up to some kind of expectations.<br/><br/>I&apos;m not sure how I would f</span>
  <span id="freeText3129195083501211670" style="display:none">I'm not sure I understood this novel. It would be easy to dismiss the characters because they are too selfish, or too amoral. By today's standards the violence and verbal abuse seem trivalized as when it's done, the characters easily forget and bear little to no grudges. I did want to find out what was happening but in the end, it seemed all they wanted to do was mostly drink, screw, and abuse each other because someone else isn't living up to some kind of expectations.<br /><br />I'm not sure how I would frame the novel or its plot as an improvement. If anything the amorality suggested that people find their way through life the best they can, and conventions are not much that matters. We get a huge contrast here between the mother and daughter, with the daughter living up to her role and being unhappy passively whereas the mother is unhappy actively. I suppose if there is any uplifting quality in the novel it's that women form a social bond between each other that keeps them going, whereas these men stick around for purely individualistic selfish reasons.<br /><br />Like any existentialistic story that is about "ordinary" bourgeois people, they live in ignorance of each other due to some kind of social convention (in this case, under the figure of marriage) until one of them gets ill, lost or dies. Then they are forced to appreciate one another. I suppose that's something, even if it seems vaguely depressing to me. The best anyone seems able to do is care for another in a vaguely mediocre, self centered way, to let them live their lives best they know how.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3129195083501211670" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

